'''''Crazy Comets''''' is a [[shoot 'em up]] programmed by Simon Nicol for the [[Commodore 64]] and published by [[Martech]] in 1985.<ref name="giantlist"/> The game is a clone of Gottlieb's 1983 ''[[Mad Planets]]'' arcade game,<ref name=zzap8/> even using the same logo treatment with "Crazy" and "Comets" replacing "Mad" and "Planets" respectively. The two music tracks and the sound effects were produced by [[Rob Hubbard]].<ref name="kultpower.de">{{cite web|url=http://www.kultpower.de/archiv/heft_happycomputer_spielesonderheft-2_seite14|title=Kultpower Archiv: Komplettscan Happy Computer Spielesonderheft 2 (1986)|website=www.kultpower.de|access-date=24 March 2018}}</ref> ''Crazy Comets'' was followed by a 1987 sequel, also programmed by Nicol, ''[[Mega Apocalypse]]''.

==Reception==
''[[Zzap!64]]'' praised the game for being an uncomplicated example of the genre.<ref name=zzap8>{{cite journal|url=https://archive.org/details/zzap64-magazine-008|journal=Zzap!64 |issue=8 |date=December 1985 |pages=35 |access-date=24 March 2018 |title=Zzap! Test: Crazy Comets}}</ref> ''Happy Computer'' said the music alone was worth the price of admission.<ref name="kultpower.de"/>

